      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Property Styling When Selling in Brisbane: What Is Worth Spending and What Is Not
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Professional styling can lift your sale result -- but it is not always worth it, and the rooms that matter vary more than most agents let on.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Property styling gets recommended as a matter of course by most agents in Brisbane's inner east. The pitch is consistent: styled homes sell faster and for more money, so the cost pays for itself. That claim is broadly true for the right property type and price range -- but it is not universally true, and the specific advice you get from a stylist your agent refers you to does not always put your interests first.</p>

      <p>The honest version is this: styling delivers a measurable return when it solves a specific problem buyers have with a property's presentation, and it delivers very little when the property is already well-presented or when sale price is being driven by land value rather than the dwelling. Knowing which situation you are in before you spend $6,000 on furniture hire is worth more than any styling consultation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What professional property styling actually involves</h2>
      <p>Styling is not the same as renovation. A stylist is not fixing anything structural or cosmetic -- they are curating the visual and emotional experience of your home during the marketing campaign. In practice this means: hiring furniture to replace dated or mismatched pieces, introducing neutral soft furnishings and artwork, decluttering surfaces and removing personal items, and arranging rooms so they photograph well and feel proportionally generous to visitors at open homes.</p>

      <p>A full styling package for a three to four bedroom Brisbane home typically runs from $3,500 to $8,000 for a six to eight week campaign. That cost covers the furniture hire, delivery and collection, the stylist's consultation fee, and the installation. Larger prestige homes, or properties with substantial indoor-outdoor living areas, can run $10,000 to $18,000. Those are real costs, not marketing noise, and they need to be assessed against what comparable styled sales in your price bracket actually achieved relative to unstyled properties.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Which rooms deliver the most impact</h2>
      <p>The living room is the single most important room to get right. Buyers form their strongest impression here, and it is the room that appears in most of the photography. A living room with dated furniture, cluttered surfaces, or poor proportions can suppress buyer interest more than almost any other factor. Replacing tired lounges and adding a styled coffee table, rug, and considered lighting makes an immediate and photographable difference.</p>

      <p>The master bedroom is the second most important space. Brisbane buyers in the $900,000 to $1.8 million range -- the bulk of the inner-east market -- are buying a lifestyle as much as a dwelling, and the master bedroom is where that aspiration is felt most directly. Hotel-quality linen, a simple bedside arrangement, and the removal of personal items transforms an average room into something buyers can picture themselves in.</p>

      <p>Outdoor entertaining space is the third priority for Queensland properties specifically. Inner-east buyers expect a functional outdoor area. If your deck or patio is well-maintained but poorly furnished, styling can turn it into a genuine selling point. A simple outdoor dining setting, some potted plants, and considered lighting can make an outdoor area read as a genuine extension of the living space rather than an afterthought.</p>

      <p>The kitchen needs decluttering and accessorising rather than staging. Remove everything from benchtops except two or three intentional items. Clean and replace anything that is visibly worn. A new kettle and a bowl of fruit will not transform a dated kitchen, but a staged kitchen with a styled benchtop and fresh hand towels can make the same space feel considered and cared for. The return from a full styling package in the kitchen is lower than the living and bedroom areas.</p>

      <p>Spare bedrooms, home offices, and utility spaces have minimal impact on buyer perception in most cases. A clean, empty spare room with fresh paint reads fine to buyers. Do not spend money styling a fourth bedroom unless you have been explicitly advised that buyer traffic in your price range is particularly focused on multi-bedroom configuration.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The evidence for styling ROI in Brisbane's inner east</h2>
      <p>Styled properties in Brisbane's inner east consistently generate stronger photography, higher open-home attendance, and more competitive early offer activity compared to comparable unstyled listings. That pattern is visible in days-on-market data and in comparative sale prices at similar address types. The strongest returns are concentrated in the $750,000 to $2 million range where owner-occupier buyers dominate and presentation premium is most consistently priced in by the market.</p>

      <p>The effect is not uniform. A Queenslander on a development-size block in Morningside or Norman Park where buyers are predominantly developers or land-bankers will not achieve a measurable styling premium -- the sale price is land-driven, not dwelling-driven. An investor selling a tenant-occupied unit will also see minimal return from styling, since vacant possession for an open-home campaign is often not practical and the buyer pool skews toward yield-focused purchasers who are not primarily moved by presentation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When styling is not worth it</h2>
      <p>There are clear situations where styling returns are low and you should resist pressure to spend. A property that is already well-presented with quality, neutral existing furniture does not need a full styling package -- decluttering and accessorising is usually sufficient and costs a fraction of the price. A property in a price range or location where buyers are primarily land or development focused gains little from dwelling presentation. A distressed sale where speed matters more than achieving the highest possible price, and where budget is constrained, should prioritise marketing reach and price positioning over presentation spend.</p>

      <p>The question to ask your agent is specific: based on comparable sales in this street and price bracket, what styling premium has actually been achieved by styled properties versus unstyled? If they cannot give you a concrete answer, or if the answer is vague, that should inform how you weigh the recommendation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Styling versus renovation: what buyers actually respond to</h2>
      <p>Buyers in Brisbane's inner east do not pay a renovation premium for cosmetic upgrades completed immediately before sale -- they consistently discount for risk. A freshly painted interior that covers walls full of hairline cracks is read as an attempt to hide problems. New carpet over a damaged subfloor is noted. Buyers know when something has been done quickly and cheaply, and it raises their suspicion about what else has not been addressed.</p>

      <p>The distinction matters because agents frequently advise vendors to renovate before selling when the cost-benefit case is weak. A full bathroom renovation completed six weeks before listing will rarely return its full cost at sale. Re-tiling a bathroom that is dated but structurally sound rarely adds a dollar of value for every dollar spent. The question to ask is whether the issue is presentation (styling can address it) or genuine condition (then it is a negotiation point regardless).</p>

      <p>Address structural maintenance items before spending on presentation. A leaking roof, damaged ceilings, visible timber rot, or non-compliant pool fencing will all be found in pre-purchase inspections and will reduce offers by more than any styling can add. Fix the items that go into reports first, then consider presentation spend second.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to brief a stylist and what to watch for</h2>
      <p>When you engage a stylist, give them a clear brief: the target buyer profile for your property, the comparable sales your agent has provided, and the budget ceiling you have set for styling. Ask them explicitly which rooms they recommend styling, why, and what result they expect. Ask whether the furniture they provide is from their own hire inventory or a third-party catalogue, since hire inventory can vary significantly in quality.</p>

      <p>Watch for recommendations that extend beyond the genuinely high-impact rooms. A stylist who recommends full staging of six rooms in a property where the living, master, and outdoor space are the clear priorities may be optimising their job rather than your result. Similarly, if your agent is referring you to a specific stylist and the cost seems high relative to the scope, it is reasonable to request quotes from one or two alternatives.</p>

      <p>The goal of styling is to allow buyers to form a clear, emotionally positive impression of the property quickly and to remove the friction that incomplete or dated presentation creates. When it is done well on the right property, it is one of the highest-returning pre-sale investments available. When it is over-applied or applied to the wrong property type, the money would have been better spent on better photography or a more targeted marketing campaign.</p>

